1782845700 · search_document x2 (1 zero-result on "the first Terry condition" italics; recovered via "armed and dangerous" x7) · ok · Arizona v. Johnson · 145912 · pre-2015 combined-opinion (2009; U.S.-Reports paginated). passenger frisk during traffic stop. two conditions "First, the investigatory stop must be lawful...Second...the police officer must reasonably suspect that the person stopped is armed and dangerous" *326-327; holding "in a traffic-stop setting, the first Terry condition...is met whenever it is lawful for police to detain an automobile and its occupants...The police need not have, in addition, cause to believe any occupant...is involved in criminal activity. To justify a patdown...the police must harbor reasonable suspicion that the person subjected to the frisk is armed and dangerous" *327; "a police officer effectively seizes everyone in the vehicle" (Brendlin) *327. good law. home=[[Traffic Stops]] Progeny + [[Terry Stops and Reasonable Suspicion]] Related. stem distinct from Johnson v. United States
